    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-09-18T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-09-18T06:00:00-05:00" n="468"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760F.62/877: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-09-18T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 18, 1938—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received September 18—9:40
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>252. …</p>
                <p>Discussing the Jewish aspect of racial policy Mussolini declared<note n="35"
                        xml:id="d468fn35">Speech of September 18, 1938, at Trieste on the
                        international situation.</note> the regime’s policy had been determined by
                    the irreconcilable hostility of international Jewry toward Fascism during the
                    past 16 years despite the regime’s tolerance. Italian Jews who had undisputed
                        <pb facs="0600" n="592" xml:id="pg_592"/> civil and military merits
                    vis-à-vis Italy and the regime would encounter understanding and justice; to the
                    others would be applied a policy of separation. The world would ultimately have
                    to admire the firmness and generosity of Italian policy unless the Jews at home
                    and abroad and their many unexpected friends forced a sudden revision.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
